igrant sentiment in Montreal, and work by Iroquois photographer Jeff Thomas. Taken together, the writings in Imagining Resistance touch on the local, the global, the national, and post-national to imagine a very different landscape of cultural practice in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aArtxPolitical aspectszCanada. 0aPolitics in artvCase studies. 0aPolitics in art. 4aArt. 4aCultural Studies. 7aART / History / Contemporary (1945-).2bisacsh1 aCronin, J. Keri, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRobertson, Kirsty, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978311127721940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781554583119423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781554583119/original  a978-3-11-127414-0  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-127721-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010c2010d2011  aGBV-deGruyter-alles